[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] For supervised learning applications in machine learning and statistical learning theory, **generalization error** (also known as the **out-of-sample error** or the **risk**) is a measure of how accurately an algorithm is able to predict outcomes for previously unseen data.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] As learning algorithms are evaluated on finite samples, the evaluation of a learning algorithm may be sensitive to sampling error.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] As a result, measurements of prediction error on the current data may not provide much information about the algorithm's predictive ability on new, unseen data.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The generalization error can be minimized by avoiding overfitting in the learning algorithm.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The performance of machine learning algorithms is commonly visualized by learning curve plots that show estimates of the generalization error throughout the learning process.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] In a learning problem, the goal is to develop a function $f_{n}({\vec {x}})$ that predicts output values y for each input datum ${\vec {x}}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The subscript n indicates that the function $f_{n}$ is developed based on a data set of n data points.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] where $\rho ({\vec {x}},y)$ is the unknown joint probability distribution for ${\vec {x}}$ and y .
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] Without knowing the joint probability distribution $\rho$ , it is impossible to compute $I[f]$ .
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] Instead, we can compute the error on sample data, which is called **empirical error** (or **empirical risk**).
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] Of particular importance is the **generalization error** $I[f_{n}]$ of the data-dependent function $f_{n}$ that is found by a learning algorithm based on the sample.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] Again, for an unknown probability distribution, $I[f_{n}]$ cannot be computed.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] That is, the goal is to characterize the probability $1-\delta _{n}$ that the generalization error is less than the empirical error plus some error bound $\epsilon$ (generally dependent on $\delta$ and n ).
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] For many types of algorithms, it has been shown that an algorithm has generalization bounds if it meets certain stability criteria.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] Specifically, if an algorithm is symmetric (the order of inputs does not affect the result), has bounded loss and meets two stability conditions, it will generalize.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The first stability condition, leave-one-out cross-validation stability, says that to be stable, the prediction error for each data point when leave-one-out cross validation is used must converge to zero as $n\rightarrow \infty$ .
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The second condition, expected-to-leave-one-out error stability (also known as hypothesis stability if operating in the $L_{1}$ norm) is met if the prediction on a left-out datapoint does not change when a single data point is removed from the training dataset.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] with $\beta _{H}^{(n)}$ going to zero as n goes to infinity.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] A number of algorithms have been proven to be stable and as a result have bounds on their generalization error.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] A list of these algorithms and the papers that proved stability is available here.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The concepts of generalization error and overfitting are closely related.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] Overfitting occurs when the learned function $f_{S}$ becomes sensitive to the noise in the sample.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] As a result, the function will perform well on the training set but not perform well on other data from the joint probability distribution of x and y .
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] Thus, the more overfitting occurs, the larger the generalization error.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The amount of overfitting can be tested using cross-validation methods, that split the sample into simulated training samples and testing samples.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The model is then trained on a training sample and evaluated on the testing sample.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The testing sample is previously unseen by the algorithm and so represents a random sample from the joint probability distribution of x and y .
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] This test sample allows us to approximate the expected error and as a result approximate a particular form of the generalization error.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] Many algorithms exist to prevent overfitting.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The minimization algorithm can penalize more complex functions (known as Tikhonov regularization), or the hypothesis space can be constrained, either explicitly in the form of the functions or by adding constraints to the minimization function (Ivanov regularization).
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] The approach to finding a function that does not overfit is at odds with the goal of finding a function that is sufficiently complex to capture the particular characteristics of the data.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] This is known as the bias–variance tradeoff.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] Keeping a function simple to avoid overfitting may introduce a bias in the resulting predictions, while allowing it to be more complex leads to overfitting and a higher variance in the predictions.
[src:vc-dimension/generalization-error] It is impossible to minimize both simultaneously.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] The **growth function**, also called the **shatter coefficient** or the **shattering number**, measures the richness of a set family or class of functions.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] It is especially used in the context of statistical learning theory, where it is used to study properties of statistical learning methods.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] The term 'growth function' was coined by Vapnik and Chervonenkis in their 1968 paper, where they also proved many of its properties.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] It is a basic concept in machine learning.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] Let H be a set family (a set of sets) and C a set.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] The *intersection-size* (also called the *index*) of H with respect to C is $|H\cap C|$ .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] If a set $C_{m}$ has m elements then the index is at most $2^{m}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] The growth function measures the size of $H\cap C$ as a function of $|C|$ .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] Equivalently, let H be a hypothesis-class (a set of binary functions) and C a set with m elements.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] The main property that makes the growth function interesting is that it can be either polynomial or exponential - nothing in-between.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] This implies the following property of the Growth function.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] since for every C , the number of elements in $H\cap C$ is at most $|H|$ .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] Therefore, the growth function is mainly interesting when H is infinite.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] I.e, the growth function has an exponential upper-bound.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] We say that a set-family H **shatters** a set C if their intersection contains all possible subsets of C , i.e. $H\cap C=2^{C}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] If H shatters C of size m , then $\operatorname {Growth} (H,C)=2^{m}$ , which is the upper bound.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] So $\operatorname {VCDim} (H)\geq d$ if-and-only-if $\operatorname {Growth} (H,d)=2^{d}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] The growth function can be regarded as a refinement of the concept of VC dimension.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] The VC dimension only tells us whether $\operatorname {Growth} (H,d)$ is equal to or smaller than $2^{d}$ , while the growth function tells us exactly how $\operatorname {Growth} (H,m)$ changes as a function of m .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] The intersection-size has the following property.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] Moreover, the sequence $\operatorname {Entropy} (H,m)/m$ converges to a constant $c\in [0,1]$ when $m\to \infty$ .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] Moreover, the random-variable $\log _{2}{|H\cap C_{m}|/m}$ is concentrated near c .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] Let $\Omega$ be a set on which a probability measure $\Pr$ is defined.
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] Let H be family of subsets of $\Omega$ (= a family of events).
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] Suppose we choose a set $C_{m}$ that contains m elements of $\Omega$ , where each element is chosen at random according to the probability measure P , independently of the others (i.e., with replacements).
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] In words: the probability that for *all* events in H , the relative-frequency is near the probability, is lower-bounded by an expression that depends on the growth-function of H .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] A corollary of this is that, if the growth function is polynomial in m (i.e., there exists some n such that $\operatorname {Growth} (H,m)\leq m^{n}+1$ ), then the above probability approaches 1 as $m\to \infty$ .
[src:vc-dimension/growth-function] I.e, the family H enjoys uniform convergence in probability.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] In computational learning theory (machine learning and theory of computation), **Rademacher complexity**, named after Hans Rademacher, measures richness of a class of sets with respect to a probability distribution.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The concept can also be extended to real valued functions.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Some authors take the absolute value of the sum before taking the supremum, but if A is symmetric this makes no difference.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Let $S=\{z_{1},z_{2},\dots ,z_{m}\}\subseteq Z$ be a sample of points and consider a function class ${\mathcal {F}}$ of real-valued functions over Z .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The **worst case empirical Rademacher complexity** is ${\overline {\operatorname {Rad} }}_{m}({\mathcal {F}})=\sup _{S=\{z_{1},\dots ,z_{m}\}}\operatorname {Rad} _{S}({\mathcal {F}})$ Let P be a probability distribution over Z .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] where the above expectation is taken over an identically independently distributed (i.i.d.) sample $S=(z_{1},z_{2},\dots ,z_{m})$ generated according to P .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The Rademacher complexity is typically applied on a function class of models that are used for classification, with the goal of measuring their ability to classify points drawn from a probability space under arbitrary labellings.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] When the function class is rich enough, it contains functions that can appropriately adapt for each arrangement of labels, simulated by the random draw of $\sigma _{i}$ under the expectation, so that this quantity in the sum is maximized.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The directions are along the vertices of a hypercube.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] In words, this states that $2{\sqrt {m}}\operatorname {Rad} (A)$ is precisely the average width of the set A along all diagonal directions of a hypercube.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] A singleton set has 0 width in any direction, so it has Rademacher complexity 0.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The set $A=\{(1,1),(1,2)\}\subseteq \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ has average width $1/{\sqrt {2}}$ along the two diagonal directions of the square, so it has Rademacher complexity $1/4$ .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The unit cube $[0,1]^{m}$ has constant width ${\sqrt {m}}$ along the diagonal directions, so it has Rademacher complexity $1/2$ .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Similarly, the unit cross-polytope $\{x\in \mathbb {R} ^{m}:\|x\|_{1}\leq 1\}$ has constant width $2/{\sqrt {m}}$ along the diagonal directions, so it has Rademacher complexity $1/m$ .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The Rademacher complexity can be used to derive data-dependent upper-bounds on the learnability of function classes.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Intuitively, a function-class with smaller Rademacher complexity is easier to learn.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] In machine learning, it is desired to have a training set that represents the true distribution of some sample data S .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] This can be quantified using the notion of **representativeness**.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Denote by P the probability distribution from which the samples are drawn.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] For example, in the case that h represents a binary classifier, the error function is a 0–1 loss function, i.e. the error function $f_{h}$ returns 0 if h correctly classifies a sample and 1 else.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] We omit the index and write f instead of $f_{h}$ when the underlying hypothesis is irrelevant.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Smaller representativeness is better, since it provides a way to avoid overfitting: it means that the true error of a classifier is not much higher than its estimated error, and so selecting a classifier that has low estimated error will ensure that the true error is also low.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Note however that the concept of representativeness is relative and hence can not be compared across distinct samples.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The Rademacher complexity is a theoretical justification for empirical risk minimization.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Let the Bayes risk $L^{*}=\inf _{f}L_{P}(f)$ , where f can be *any* measurable function.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Let the function class ${\mathcal {F}}$ be split into "complexity classes" ${\mathcal {F}}_{r}$ , where $r\in \mathbb {R}$ are levels of complexity.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Let the complexity measure function p be defined such that $p(f):=\min\{p_{r}:f\in {\mathcal {F}}_{r}\}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] For any dataset S , let ${\hat {f}}$ be a minimizer of $L_{S}(f)+p(f)$ .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Since smaller Rademacher complexity is better, it is useful to have upper bounds on the Rademacher complexity of various function sets.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The following rules can be used to upper-bound the Rademacher complexity of a set $A\subset \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Let H be a set family whose VC dimension is d .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] This means that, for every set h with at most m elements, $|H\cap h|\leq (em/d)^{d}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The set-family $H\cap h$ can be considered as a set of binary vectors over $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The following bounds are related to linear operations on S – a constant set of m vectors in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The following bound relates the Rademacher complexity of a set A to its external covering number – the number of balls of a given radius r whose union contains A .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] Suppose $A\subset \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ is a set of vectors whose length (norm) is at most c .
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] As an example, consider the rademacher and gaussian complexities of the L1 ball.
[src:vc-dimension/rademacher-complexity] The Rademacher complexity is given by exactly 1, whereas the Gaussian complexity is on the order of ${\sqrt {\log d}}$ (which can be shown by applying known properties of suprema of a set of subgaussian random variables).
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] In combinatorial mathematics and extremal set theory, the **Sauer–Shelah lemma** states that every family of sets with small VC dimension consists of a small number of sets.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Here, the VC dimension is the largest size k of a set with the property that all of its subsets can be formed by intersecting it with a member of the family.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] If the family has n elements in its union, then the Sauer–Shelah lemma states that its number of sets is at most proportional to $n^{k}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] It is named after Norbert Sauer and Saharon Shelah, who published it independently of each other in 1972.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] The same result was also published slightly earlier, and again independently, by Vladimir Vapnik and Alexey Chervonenkis, after whom the VC dimension is named.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] In his paper containing the lemma, Shelah gives credit also to Micha Perles, and for this reason the lemma has also been called the **Perles–Sauer–Shelah lemma** and the **Sauer–Shelah–Perles lemma**.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Buzaglo et al. call this lemma "one of the most fundamental results on VC-dimension", and it has applications in many areas.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Sauer's motivation was in the combinatorics of set systems, while Shelah's was in model theory and that of Vapnik and Chervonenkis was in statistics.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] It has also been applied in discrete geometry and graph theory.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] If $\textstyle {\mathcal {F}}=\{S_{1},S_{2},\dots \}$ is a family of sets and T is a set, then T is said to be shattered by ${\mathcal {F}}$ if every subset of T (including the empty set and T itself) can be obtained as the intersection $T\cap S_{i}$ of T with some set $S_{i}$ in the family.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] The VC dimension of ${\mathcal {F}}$ is the largest cardinality of a set shattered by ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] In terms of these definitions, the Sauer–Shelah lemma states that if the VC dimension of ${\mathcal {F}}$ is k , and the union of ${\mathcal {F}}$ has n elements, then ${\mathcal {F}}$ can consist of at most $\sum _{i=0}^{k}{\binom {n}{i}}=O(n^{k})$ sets, as expressed using big O notation.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Equivalently, if the number of sets in the family, $|{\mathcal {F}}|$ , obeys the inequality $|{\mathcal {F}}|>\sum _{i=0}^{k-1}{\binom {n}{i}},$ then there exists a set of size k that ${\mathcal {F}}$ shatters.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] The bound of the lemma is tight: Let the family ${\mathcal {F}}$ be composed of all subsets of $\{1,2,\dots ,n\}$ with size less than k .
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Then the number of sets in ${\mathcal {F}}$ is exactly ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{k-1}{\binom {n}{i}}}$ but it does not shatter any set of size k , because the set itself cannot be obtained as an intersection with a set in this family.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] A strengthening of the Sauer–Shelah lemma, due to Pajor (1985), states that every finite set family ${\mathcal {F}}$ shatters at least $|{\mathcal {F}}|$ sets.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] This immediately implies the Sauer–Shelah lemma, because only ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{k-1}{\tbinom {n}{i}}}$ of the subsets of an n -item universe have cardinality less than k .
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Thus, when $|{\mathcal {F}}|>\sum _{i=0}^{k-1}{\binom {n}{i}},$ there are not enough small sets to be shattered, so one of the shattered sets must have cardinality at least k .
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] For a restricted type of shattered set, called an order-shattered set, the number of shattered sets always equals the cardinality of the set family.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Pajor's variant of the Sauer–Shelah lemma may be proved by mathematical induction; the proof has variously been credited to Noga Alon or to Ron Aharoni and Ron Holzman.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Every family of only one set shatters the empty set.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] that belongs to some but not all of the sets.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Some of the shattered sets may be shattered by both subfamilies.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] A different proof of the Sauer–Shelah lemma in its original form, by Péter Frankl and János Pach, is based on linear algebra and the inclusion–exclusion principle.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] This proof extends to other settings such as families of vector spaces and, more generally, geometric lattices.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] A set S of (unweighted) samples is said to be an $\varepsilon$ -net if every event with probability at least $\varepsilon$ includes at least one point of S .
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] An $\varepsilon$ -approximation must also be an $\varepsilon$ -net but not necessarily vice versa.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] In turn, $\varepsilon$ -nets and $\varepsilon$ -approximations, and the likelihood that a random sample of large enough cardinality has these properties, have important applications in machine learning, in the area of probably approximately correct learning.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] In computational geometry, they have been applied to range searching, derandomization, and approximation algorithms.
[src:vc-dimension/sauer-shelah-lemma] Kozma & Moran (2013) use generalizations of the Sauer–Shelah lemma to prove results in graph theory such as that the number of strong orientations of a given graph is sandwiched between its numbers of connected and 2-edge-connected subgraphs.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] A class of sets is said to shatter another set if it is possible to "pick out" any element of that set using intersection.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] The concept of **shattered sets** plays an important role in Vapnik–Chervonenkis theory, also known as VC-theory.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Shattering and VC-theory are used in the study of empirical processes as well as in statistical computational learning theory.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Suppose *A* is a set and *C* is a class of sets.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Equivalently, *C* shatters *A* when their intersection is equal to *A'*s power set: *P*(*A*) = { *c* ∩ *A* | *c* ∈ *C* }.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] We employ the letter *C* to refer to a "class" or "collection" of sets, as in a Vapnik–Chervonenkis class (VC-class).
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] The set *A* is often assumed to be finite because, in empirical processes, we are interested in the shattering of finite sets of data points.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] We will show that the class of all discs in the plane (two-dimensional space) does not shatter every set of four points on the unit circle, yet the class of all convex sets in the plane does shatter every finite set of points on the unit circle.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Let *A* be a set of four points on the unit circle and let *C* be the class of all discs.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] To test where *C* shatters *A*, we attempt to draw a disc around every subset of points in *A*.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] First, we draw a disc around the subsets of each isolated point.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Next, we try to draw a disc around every subset of point pairs.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] This turns out to be doable for adjacent points, but impossible for points on opposite sides of the circle.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Any attempt to include those points on the opposite side will necessarily include other points not in that pair.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Hence, any pair of opposite points cannot be isolated out of *A* using intersections with class *C* and so *C* does not shatter *A*.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Because there is some subset which can *not* be isolated by any disc in *C*, we conclude then that *A* is not shattered by *C*.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] And, with a bit of thought, we can prove that no set of four points is shattered by this *C*.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] However, if we redefine *C* to be the class of all *elliptical discs*, we find that we can still isolate all the subsets from above, as well as the points that were formerly problematic.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Thus, this specific set of 4 points is shattered by the class of elliptical discs.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] With a bit of thought, we could generalize that any set of finite points on a unit circle could be shattered by the class of all convex sets (visualize connecting the dots).
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] To quantify the richness of a collection *C* of sets, we use the concept of *shattering coefficients* (also known as the *growth function*).
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] where $\operatorname {card}$ denotes the cardinality of the set and $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}\in \Omega$ is any set of *n* points,.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] $S_{C}(n)$ is the largest number of subsets of any set *A* of *n* points that can be formed by intersecting *A* with the sets in collection *C*.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] For example, if set *A* contains 3 points, its power set, $P(A)$ , contains $2^{3}=8$ elements.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] If *C* shatters *A*, its shattering coefficient(3) would be 8 and $S_{C}(2)$ would be $2^{2}=4$ .
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] However, if one of those sets in $P(A)$ cannot be obtained through intersections in *c*, then $S_{C}(3)$ would only be 7.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] If none of those sets can be obtained, $S_{C}(3)$ would be 0.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Additionally, if $S_{C}(2)=3$ , for example, then there is an element in the set of all 2-point sets from *A* that cannot be obtained from intersections with *C*.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] It follows from this that $S_{C}(3)$ would also be less than 8 (i.e.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] *C* would not shatter *A*) because we have already located a "missing" set in the smaller power set of 2-point sets.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] If $S_{C}(n)=2^{n}$ , that means there is a set of cardinality *n*, which can be shattered by *C*.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] The third property means that if *C* cannot shatter any set of cardinality *N* then it can not shatter sets of larger cardinalities.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] If *A* cannot be shattered by *C*, there will be a smallest value of *n* that makes the shatter coefficient(n) less than $2^{n}$ because as *n* gets larger, there are more sets that could be missed.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Alternatively, there is also a largest value of *n* for which the $S_{C}(n)$ is still $2^{n}$ , because as *n* gets smaller, there are fewer sets that could be omitted.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] The extreme of this is $S_{C}(0)$ (the shattering coefficient of the empty set), which must always be $2^{0}=1$ .
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] The VC dimension is usually defined as $VC_{0}$ , the largest cardinality of points chosen that will still shatter *A* (i.e.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] Alternatively, if for any *n* there is a set of cardinality *n* which can be shattered by *C*, then $S_{C}(n)=2^{n}$ for all *n* and the VC dimension of this class *C* is infinite.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] A class with finite VC dimension is called a *Vapnik–Chervonenkis class* or *VC class*.
[src:vc-dimension/shattered-set] A class *C* is uniformly Glivenko–Cantelli if and only if it is a VC class.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] In Vapnik–Chervonenkis theory, the **Vapnik–Chervonenkis (VC) dimension** is a measure of the size (capacity, complexity, expressive power, richness, or flexibility) of a class of sets.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The notion can be extended to classes of binary functions.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] It is defined as the cardinality of the largest set of points that the function class can shatter—that is, for which all possible binary labelings can be realized by some function in the class.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] It was originally defined by Vladimir Vapnik and Alexey Chervonenkis.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Informally, the capacity of a classification model is related to how complicated it can be.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] For example, consider the thresholding of a high-degree polynomial: if the polynomial evaluates above zero, that point is classified as positive, otherwise as negative.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] A high-degree polynomial can be wiggly, so that it can fit a given set of training points well.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] A much simpler alternative is to threshold a linear function.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] This function may not fit the training set well, because it has a low capacity.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] This notion of capacity is made rigorous below.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Let ${\mathcal {C}}=\{C\}_{C\in {\mathcal {C}}}$ be a family of sets (also called set family, collection of sets, or set of sets) and X be a set.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Here typically X and each $C\in {\mathcal {C}}$ are subsets of a big "universe" of possibilities U where intersection takes place.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] We say that a set X is *shattered* by ${\mathcal {C}}$ if ${\mathcal {P}}(X)={\mathcal {C}}\cap X$ i.e. the set of intersections contains (hence is equal to the set of) all the subsets of X .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The *VC dimension* D of ${\mathcal {C}}$ is the cardinality of the largest set that is shattered by ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] If arbitrarily large sets can be shattered, the VC dimension of ${\mathcal {C}}$ is $\infty$ .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Consider a binary classification model f with some parameter vector $\theta$ , a set of generally positioned data points $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] We say that the model f shatters $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}$ if, for every assignment of labels to those points, there exists a vector $\theta$ such that the model f makes no errors when evaluating that set of data points.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of a model f is the maximum number of points that can be arranged so that f shatters them.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] More formally, it is the maximum cardinal D such that there exists a generally positioned data point set of cardinality D that can be shattered by f .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] 2. f is a single-parametric threshold classifier on real numbers; i.e., for a certain threshold $\theta$ , the classifier $f_{\theta }$ returns 1 if the input number is larger than $\theta$ and 0 otherwise.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of f is 1 because: (a) It can shatter a single point.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] For every point x , a classifier $f_{\theta }$ labels it as 0 if $\theta >x$ and labels it as 1 if $\theta <x$ .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] (b) It cannot shatter all the sets with two points.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] For every set of two numbers, if the smaller is labeled 1, then the larger must also be labeled 1, so not all labelings are possible.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] 3. f is a single-parametric interval classifier on real numbers; i.e., for a certain parameter $\theta$ , the classifier $f_{\theta }$ returns 1 if the input number is in the interval $[\theta ,\theta +4]$ and 0 otherwise.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of f is 2 because: (a) It can shatter some sets of two points.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] (b) It cannot shatter any set of three points.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] For every set of three numbers, if the smallest and the largest are labeled 1, then the middle one must also be labeled 1, so not all labelings are possible.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] 4. f is a straight line as a classification model on points in a two-dimensional plane (this is the model used by a perceptron).
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The line should separate positive data points from negative data points.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] There exist sets of 3 points that can indeed be shattered using this model (any 3 points that are not collinear can be shattered).
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] However, no set of 4 points can be shattered: by Radon's theorem, any four points can be partitioned into two subsets with intersecting convex hulls, so it is not possible to separate one of these two subsets from the other.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Thus, the VC dimension of this particular classifier is 3.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] It is important to remember that while one can choose any arrangement of points, the arrangement of those points cannot change when attempting to shatter for some label assignment.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Note, only 3 of the 23 = 8 possible label assignments are shown for the three points.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] 5. f is a single-parametric sine classifier, i.e., for a certain parameter $\theta$ , the classifier $f_{\theta }$ returns 1 if the input number x has $\sin(\theta x)>0$ and 0 otherwise.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of f is infinite, since it can shatter any finite subset of the set $\{2^{-m}\mid m\in \mathbb {N} \}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension can predict a probabilistic upper bound on the test error of a classification model.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] where D is the VC dimension of the classification model, $0<\eta \leqslant 1$ , and N is the size of the training set (restriction: this formula is valid when $D\ll N$ .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] When D is larger, the test-error may be much higher than the training-error.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension also appears in sample-complexity bounds.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] samples, where $\varepsilon$ is the learning error and $\delta$ is the failure probability.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Thus, the sample-complexity is a linear function of the VC dimension of the hypothesis space.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension is one of the critical parameters in the size of ε-nets, which determines the complexity of approximation algorithms based on them; range sets without finite VC dimension may not have finite ε-nets at all.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of the dual set-family of ${\mathcal {C}}$ is strictly less than $2^{\operatorname {vc} ({\mathcal {C}})+1}$ , and this is best possible.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of a finite set-family ${\mathcal {C}}$ is at most $\log _{2}|{\mathcal {C}}|$ .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] This is because $|{\mathcal {C}}\cap X|\leq |X|$ by definition.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Given a set-family ${\mathcal {C}}$ , define ${\mathcal {C}}_{s}$ as a set-family that contains all intersections of s elements of ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Given a set-family ${\mathcal {C}}$ and an element $C_{0}\in {\mathcal {C}}$ , define ${\mathcal {C}}\,\Delta C_{0}:=\{C\,\Delta C_{0}\mid C\in H\}$ where $\Delta$ denotes symmetric set difference.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension of a finite projective plane is 2.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Suppose we have a base class B of simple classifiers, whose VC dimension is D .
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] We can construct a more powerful classifier by combining several different classifiers from B ; this technique is called boosting.
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] The VC dimension is defined for spaces of binary functions (functions to {0,1}).
[src:vc-dimension/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension] Several generalizations have been suggested for spaces of non-binary functions.
